<OPTION>Smithing (137)</SELECT>
</FORM></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uviken.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Viken</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Guardian of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 590<br> <font color=#CC9900>(7/23/01 3:45:44 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: why rock the boat when we can gently move it....</span><hr size=1> Here is a great idea that can work with the system already in place:<br>
<br>
When signing up for a raid, you absolutely must give your FR/CR + MR levels. Once you show up at the raid there will be one person responsible for checking everyone's equipment. If you don't have the appropriate equipment you don't get to raid. It's as simple as that. This might be painful for the raid leaders who are forced to pass over key people that they might need for that particular raid (say an extra cleric), but in the long run people will learn, and they will know not to bother signing up if they don't have the appropriate gear.<br>
<br>
A lot of people sign up for these raids with no raiding experience, no knowledge on the dragons, and nothing to show for resist gear. If you are signing up for a dragon raid it should be YOUR responsibility to at least spend 30 minutes reading up on strats and a few hundred pp on resist gear. You don't need thousands of pp to buy velium diamond rings etc...<br>
<br>
Cloak of the Ice Bear...70pp<br>
2 Silver Peridot Rings... 30pp<br>
2 Symbol of Loyalty to Vox...150pp<br>
<br>
For a 250pp you've just increased your CR by a whopping +44. Give this to everyone and it could mean the difference between winning and losing the raid. Resists will make all the difference. Get your mr + cr/fr over 120 and you will take little to no damage from AE, and you won't get feared. This _IS_ the difference between winning and losing.<br>
<br>
Old school players used to kill Nagafen with 3 groups. I see people taking 6 groups and failing!!! what are they doing wrong? ...inexperienced players with no resist gear. So much relies on resists and most raiders don't have a clue.<br>
<br>
Now... you might get a few:<br>
<br>
&quot;That's no fair. Just because I can't afford resist gear doesn't mean I shouldn't get to go&quot;<br>
<br>
.... uhh yes it does. As I showed above you can dramatically increase your resists for a few hundred pp. At level 46 you should have no problem finding a few hundred pp. Sell off a piece of your main gear if you have to. The dragon raid is more important. If you want to kill a dragon it should be YOUR responsibility to be prepared for that type of encounter. You are putting everyone else's lives at risk. You know how much it sucks to finally go on a dragoon raid and LOSE??? That hasn't happened to me, but I'm sure it would majorly suck ass.<br>
<br>
<br>
Conclusion:<br>
<br>
Make set requirements for cr/fr + mr gear. Different classes can have different requirements. This forces some people to be excluded from sign-ups until they can get the proper resist gear. This is a good thing. Everyone on the raid will be much better equipped, therefore, the raids will always succeed instead of sometimes failing. Those people who are prepared to go will have a much higher chance of getting picked. <br>
<br>
I estimate that 50% of raiders don't have the proper resist gear. That means those who do have a 100% better chance of getting picked (since there is less competition.) And those who do are the ones we should be carring about. <p><FORM>
